\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The propagation of intense light through optical fibers is governed by the interplay between linear dispersion and the nonlinear response of the dielectric medium.
 In silica,
 the centrosymmetric lattice eliminates second-order nonlinearity,
 so the leading nonlinear effect is the Kerr term 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{(3)}$
\end_inset

.
 Starting from Maxwell’s equations in a source-free,
 non-magnetic dielectric,
 the electric field can be written as a slowly varying envelope modulating a carrier:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{E}\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\frac{1}{2}\hat{\mathbf{x}}\left[F\left(x,y\right)A\left(z,t\right)e^{i\left(\beta_{0}z-\omega_{0}t\right)}+\text{c.c.}\right].
\]

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $F\left(x,y\right)$
\end_inset

 is the transverse modal shape set by the fiber’s refractive-index profile,
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(z,t\right)$
\end_inset

 is the envelope,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the propagation constant at the carrier frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Applying the slowly varying envelope approximation and expanding the propagation constant to second order in frequency yields the nonlinear Schrödinger equation (NLS):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i\partial_{z}A-\frac{\beta_{2}}{2}\partial_{T}^{2}A+\gamma\left|A\right|^{2}A=0,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the group-velocity-dispersion parameter and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\dfrac{n_{2}\omega_{0}}{cA_{\!\text{eff}}}$
\end_inset

 encodes the Kerr nonlinearity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In real fibers the refractive index is not spatially uniform.
 Fiber Bragg gratings impose periodic modulations,
 graded-index fibers create a parabolic transverse profile (an effective harmonic-oscillator potential),
 and photonic-crystal fibers achieve confinement via a micro-structured air-hole lattice.
 In every case,
 the spatial variation of the index enters the governing equations as an external potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The transverse modal equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nabla_{\perp}^{2}F+\left[\left(\frac{n\omega}{c}\right)^{2}\left(\mathbf{x}_{\perp}\right)-\beta^{2}\right]F=0
\]

\end_inset

is mathematically identical to the stationary Schrödinger equation 
\begin_inset Formula $-\Delta\psi+V\left(x\right)\psi=E\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Guided modes of the fiber correspond to bound states of this effective potential,
 and the fundamental mode is its ground state.
 This equivalence motivates the present work:
 engineering 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 via refractive-index design directly translates into questions about the existence,
 uniqueness,
 and stability of ground-state solutions of the NLS with an external potential.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently,
 we study the stationary NLS
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(-\Delta+V+E\right)\psi+\sigma\left|\psi\right|^{2p}\psi=0,\tag{1}\label{eq:NLS}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $V:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>0$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E\ge0$
\end_inset

.
 The parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 represents the energy (or,
 in the optical setting,
 the propagation constant).
 For each admissible 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 we seek ground-state solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{E}$
\end_inset

 and analyze how their spatial structure is governed by the geometry of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NLS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 is posed on the unbounded domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

,
 compactness is lost and standard variational methods fail.
 The concentration compactness principle introduced by Lions
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lions1984a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 classifies minimizing sequences into compactness,
 vanishing,
 or dichotomy.
 By rescaling
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{E}\left(x\right)=E^{-\frac{1}{2p}}\psi_{E}\left(E^{-\frac{1}{2}}x\right),
\]

\end_inset

(see the global bifurcation analysis of Kirr and Natarajan
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KirrNatarajan2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) one obtains a bounded family in 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Concentration compactness then yields a multi-peak decomposition:
 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{E}$
\end_inset

 is approximated by a finite sum of well-separated profiles,
 each solving the translation-invariant NLS 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(-\,\Delta+1\right)u+\sigma\left|u\right|^{2p}u=0$
\end_inset

.
 The rescaled peak positions converge to the critical points of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $E\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This multi-peak decomposition reduces the infinite-dimensional problem to a finite-dimensional system governing the peak locations.
 A Lyapunov-Schmidt reduction first solves for the orthogonal remainder and then projects onto the span of the translational modes.
 The resulting algebraic system balances the restoring force from the Hessian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{V}$
\end_inset

 of the potential against the attractive interaction between neighboring peaks:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{V}\left(x_{0}\right)y_{i}=\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\alpha_{ki}\chi\left(y_{k}-y_{i}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the rescaled peak positions,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ki}\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 are interaction coefficients,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi>0$
\end_inset

 quantifies the overall interaction strength.
 The peak set must lie in the unstable manifold of 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{V}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We classify admissible multi-peak configurations (collinear,
 coplanar,
 and triangular) by analyzing the Hessian eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1},\lambda_{2}<0$
\end_inset

 and the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\frac{\left|\lambda_{2}\right|}{\left|\lambda_{1}\right|}$
\end_inset

.
 The interaction constraints 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ki}\ge0$
\end_inset

 restrict the admissible 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mu,\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 parameter space,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the orientation of a triangle relative to the eigenvector basis.
 For example,
 an equilateral triangle requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=3\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

,
 while any triangle is admissible for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tfrac{1}{3}\le\mu\le3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our contribution is a systematic analysis of this reduced system,
 yielding explicit geometric characterizations of multi-peak ground states near non-degenerate critical points of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 The analysis extends the concentration compactness and Lyapunov-Schmidt framework by handling the nontrivial kernel of the linearized reduced system.
 By decomposing the system into parallel and perpendicular components,
 exploiting rotational symmetry,
 and constructing solutions for finite scaling parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $R=E^{-\tfrac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

,
 we obtain families of exact multi-peak solutions of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:NLS"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 for all sufficiently large energies 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

