with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{ik}\left(0\right)=e^{-\left\langle y_{k}-y_{i},\delta y_{k}-\delta y_{i}\right\rangle }\chi$
\end_inset

.
 Now consider 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\perp}F\left(\delta y^{0},0\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\parallel}F\left(\delta y^{0},0\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\perp,\parallel$
\end_inset

 are with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
 We then have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
D_{\delta y}P_{\perp}F\left(\delta y^{0},0\right)\left[\delta w\right] & =P_{\perp}\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\left\langle \delta w_{k}-\delta w_{i},y_{k}-y_{i}\right\rangle \alpha_{ik}\left(0\right)\left(y_{k}-y_{i}\right)\\
D_{\delta y}P_{\parallel}F\left(\delta y^{0},0\right)\left[\delta w\right] & =\sum_{i}\left\langle w_{i},H_{V}\delta w_{i}\right\rangle \\
 & +\sum_{i}\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\left[\left\langle w_{i},\alpha_{ki}\left(0\right)\left(\delta y_{k}^{0}-\delta y_{i}^{0}\right)\right\rangle \left\langle y_{k}-y_{i},\delta w_{k}-\delta w_{i}\right\rangle -\alpha_{ki}\left(0\right)\left\langle w_{i},\delta w_{k}-\delta w_{i}\right\rangle \right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta w\in\Gamma=\ker\left(D_{\delta y}P_{\perp}F\left(\delta y^{0},0\right)\oplus D_{\delta y}P_{\parallel}F\left(\delta y^{0},0\right)\right)\Rightarrow\delta w\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i}\left\langle w_{i},H_{V}\delta w_{i}-\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\alpha_{ki}\left(0\right)\left\langle w_{i},\delta w_{k}-\delta w_{i}\right\rangle \right\rangle =0
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta w\in\Gamma$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta w\in\Omega$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P_{\delta w} & =H_{V}\delta w_{i}-\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\alpha_{ki}\left(0\right)\left(\delta w_{k}-\delta w_{i}\right)\\
\Omega^{\perp} & \ni\\
 & =\left\{ z\in\mathbb{R}^{2\times3}|\exists c_{ki}=c_{ik}|z_{i}=\sum_{k\in N_{i}}c_{ki}\left(y_{k}-y_{i}\right)\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Claim
If we restrict 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta y_{1}$
\end_inset

 to be orthogonal to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta y_{3}-\delta y_{2}$
\end_inset

 to be parallel to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{r_{1}}$
\end_inset

.
 From 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}F_{i}\left(\delta y,R\right)=0$
\end_inset

 we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta y_{1}\left(R\right),\delta y_{2}\left(R\right),\delta y_{3}\left(R\right)$
\end_inset

 that solve 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:reduced-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta y_{1}\left(0\right)=\delta y_{1}^{0},\delta y_{2}\left(0\right)=\delta y_{2}^{0},\delta y_{3}\left(0\right)=\delta y_{3}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}F_{i}\left(\delta y,R\right)=0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{i}F_{i}\left(\delta y,R\right) & =0\\
\sum_{i}H_{V}y_{i}+H_{V}\frac{\delta y_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}}-\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\frac{2Q_{R}\left(\left|\tilde{m}_{R}\left(y_{k}-y_{i}\right)+\delta y_{k}-\delta y_{i}\right|\right)}{\left\Vert u_{R}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}^{2}R^{4}\left|\tilde{m}_{R}\left(y_{k}-y_{i}\right)+\delta y_{k}-\delta y_{i}\right|}\left(y_{k}-y_{i}+\frac{\delta y_{k}-\delta y_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}}\right) & =\\
\sum_{i}H_{V}\left(\frac{\tilde{m}_{R}y_{i}+\delta y_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}}\right)-\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\frac{2Q_{R}\left(\left|\tilde{m}_{R}\left(y_{k}-y_{i}\right)+\delta y_{k}-\delta y_{i}\right|\right)}{\left\Vert u_{R}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}^{2}R^{4}\left|\tilde{m}_{R}\left(y_{k}-y_{i}\right)+\delta y_{k}-\delta y_{i}\right|}\left(\frac{\tilde{m}_{R}y_{k}-\tilde{m}_{R}y_{i}+\delta y_{k}-\delta y_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}}\right) & =\\
\sum_{i}H_{V}\frac{\tilde{y}_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}}-\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\frac{2Q_{R}\left(\left|\tilde{m}_{R}y_{k}+\delta y_{k}-\left(\tilde{m}_{R}y_{i}+\delta y_{i}\right)\right|\right)}{\left\Vert u_{R}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}^{2}R^{4}\left|\tilde{m}_{R}y_{k}+\delta y_{k}-\left(\tilde{m}_{R}y_{i}+\delta y_{i}\right)\right|}\left(\frac{\tilde{m}_{R}y_{k}+\delta y_{k}-\left(\tilde{m}_{R}y_{i}+\delta y_{i}\right)}{\tilde{m}_{R}}\right) & =\\
\sum_{i}H_{V}\frac{\tilde{y}_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}}-\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\frac{2Q_{R}\left(\left|\tilde{y}_{k}-\tilde{y}_{i}\right|\right)}{\left\Vert u_{R}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}^{2}R^{4}\left|\tilde{y}_{k}-\tilde{y}_{i}\right|}\cdot\frac{\tilde{y}_{k}-\tilde{y}_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}} & =\\
 & \Downarrow\\
H_{V}\frac{\tilde{y}_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}}-\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\frac{2Q_{R}\left(\left|\tilde{y}_{k}-\tilde{y}_{i}\right|\right)}{\left\Vert u_{R}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}^{2}R^{4}\left|\tilde{y}_{k}-\tilde{y}_{i}\right|}\cdot\frac{\tilde{y}_{k}-\tilde{y}_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}} & =0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which is precisely 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:reduced-system"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 and since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
H_{V}\frac{\tilde{y}_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}} & =\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\frac{2Q_{R}\left(\left|\tilde{y}_{k}-\tilde{y}_{i}\right|\right)}{\left\Vert u_{R}\right\Vert _{L^{2}}^{2}R^{4}\left|\tilde{y}_{k}-\tilde{y}_{i}\right|}\cdot\frac{\tilde{y}_{k}-\tilde{y}_{i}}{\tilde{m}_{R}}\\
 & \Downarrow\:\left(R\searrow0\right)\\
H_{V}y_{i} & =\sum_{k\in N_{i}}\alpha_{ki}\chi\left(y_{k}-y_{i}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

has solutions (by construction) 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta y_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

,
 we also can see 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta y_{i}\left(0\right)=\lim_{R\searrow0}\delta y_{i}\left(R\right)=\delta y_{i}^{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More generally,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\delta y_{1},\delta y_{2},\delta y_{3}\right)\perp\left(w_{1},w_{2},w_{3}\right)=w_{\text{rot}}\iff\delta y\in\left\{ w_{\text{rot}}\right\} ^{\perp}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}\left(\delta y_{i},R\right)$
\end_inset

 does not necessarily preserve 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ w_{\text{rot}}\right\} ^{\perp}$
\end_inset

;
 however,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ w_{\text{rot}}\right\} ^{\perp}=P_{\perp_{\text{rot}}}F_{i}\left(\delta y_{i},R\right)=0$
\end_inset

 has a unique solution.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}\left(R_{w}\delta y_{i},R\right)=R_{w}F_{i}\left(\delta y_{i},R\right)$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $w\in\left[-\pi,\pi\right]$
\end_inset

,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}\left(R_{w}\delta y_{i},R\right)=0$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}\left(\delta y_{i},R\right)\mapsto R_{w}F_{i}\left(\delta y_{i},R\right)$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}\left(\delta y_{i},R\right)=0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have carried out a complete finite-dimensional study of multi-peak ground states for the nonlinear Schrödinger equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(-\Delta+V+E)\psi+\sigma|\psi|^{2p}\psi=0,\qquad E\to\infty,
\]

\end_inset

using the rescaling and concentration compactness framework.
 The existence question is reduced to an algebraic system
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{i}(\delta y,R)=0,
\]

\end_inset

which governs the positions of well-separated profiles near a non-degenerate critical point of the potential 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our main results are threefold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Classification of limiting configurations (
\begin_inset Formula $R=0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Collinear peaks along a single Hessian eigenvector.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Isosceles and equilateral triangles in the plane spanned by two eigenvectors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Equilateral triangles with a continuous rotational degree of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 For the rotational case we derived admissible regions in the 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu,\theta)-$
\end_inset

plane,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\frac{\left|\lambda_{2}\right|}{\left|\lambda_{1}\right|}$
\end_inset

.
 All orientations are admissible when 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{3}\le\mu\le3$
\end_inset

;
 otherwise only restricted angular windows remain.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Perturbation of the limiting system (
\begin_inset Formula $R>0$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We formulated the system 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}(\delta y,R)=0$
\end_inset

 and constructed explicit solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta y^{0}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $R=0$
\end_inset

 for the equilateral triangle (Claim 3).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The linearization 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\delta y}F_{i}(\delta y^{0},0)$
\end_inset

 has a nontrivial kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 containing the two-dimensional subspace of rigid translations,
 which blocks a direct application of the implicit function theorem.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Resolution strategy for the kernel obstruction.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Following the iterative kernel-decomposition method,
 we decomposed the reduced system into components perpendicular and parallel to the kernel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Gauge-fixing constraints (removing the rotational freedom) yield a projected system that is expected to admit a unique branch,
 provided the full system is rotationally equivariant.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The work stops at a precise point:
 the concentration compactness decomposition,
 the Lyapunov-Schmidt reduction,
 and the link back to the full PDE are already established.
 What remains is to finish the finite-dimensional step by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Verifying rotational equivariance of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Proving invertibility of the linearized operator on the gauge-fixed subspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Extending the analysis to configurations with a continuous rotation angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once these are done,
 the Lyapunov-Schmidt machinery lifts the finite-dimensional solutions to exact multi-peak ground states for all sufficiently large energies 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 Stability properties are largely understood:
 multi-profile branches with two or more peaks have at least two negative directions in the linearized operator,
 implying orbital instability;
 asymptotic stability of single-peak states has been established in earlier works,
 and adapting those techniques to multi-peak states remains an open problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary,
 we have classified all admissible multi-peak geometries,
 identified the kernel obstruction,
 and set up the finite-dimensional reduction.
 The remaining tasks (equivariance,
 invertibility,
 and handling of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta-$
\end_inset

dependent case) are concrete,
 finite-dimensional problems whose solution will complete the existence theory for multi-peak ground states at finite energy.
\end_layout

